Language: Ilocano
Language code: ilo
Lines: orth orth-seg gloss translat
Author: James Blackburn, Kazuki Shintani
Date: April 7, 2017
Source a: Rubino, Carl. Reference grammar of Ilocano. Diss. University of California, Santa Barbara, 1997.


######################################
######### ADJECTIVES #################
######################################

# Adjectives, which are used as attributive adjectives, in Ilocano are 
# either monomorphemic (Rubino also refers to as "simple root adjectives"),
# fossilized and derived.
# For example, in the monomorphemic adjective, the word,
# "dakkel" means "big", and "dakkel" is an adjective by itself, without
# any morphological rules applied to it.
# For fossilized adjectives have the "a-" prefix, and it is no longer
# productive once the affixation is applied and no longer be separated.
# They form a small class, expressing physical dimensions, such as "akaba" 
# meaning "wide" and "akikid" meaning "narrow".
# In addition, there is the "derived" adjective.
# Derived adjectives, as the terminology indicates, consist of a noun
# and the prefix 'na-', which is prepended to the noun. For example, the noun "angin" means
# "wind". But when the prefix "na-" is attached to the
# noun, it becomes "na-angin", and that is now an adjective, meaning "windy":
# Some examples of derived adjectives are:
# angin    wind      na-angin    windy
# pigsa    strength  na-pigsa    strong
# baknang  wealth    na-baknang  wealthy
#
# In the customization system, there was no option to do category-changing
# morphology, which is observed in the derived adjectives, and it is out of scope for the purpose
# of lab #4, at least. The choice was to just enter the "na-" adjectives directly
# into the lexicon list, without creating any adjective-specific morphological
# rules. For fossilized adjectives, because the prefix "a-" is inseparatable, lexicons were 
# entered as "akaba", "akikid", etc, without any hyphen. Rubino does not show the "a-"
# prefix in his IGT.
#
# Attributive adjectives could appear either before or after the noun, but between
# the noun and the adjective, there needs to be the ligature "a" or "nga".

# An example shows that attributive adjectives have a 
# ligature between ADJ and NOUN, in the order of ADJ LIG NOUN
Source: a:122
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {adjectives}
Kayatenko      ti      nalabaga  a   balay
Kayat-en=ko    ti      na-labaga a   balay
want-GF=1SG.ERG CORE.SG ADJ-red   LIG house
`I want the red house`

# An example shows that attributive adjectives have a 
# ligature between NOUN LIG ADJ, in the order of NOUN LIG ADJ
Source: a:139
Vetted: f
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {adjectives}
Kayatenko      ti      balay a   nalabaga
Kayat-en=ko    ti      balay a   na-labaga
want-GF=1SG.ERG CORE.SG house LIG ADJ-red
`I want the red house`

# Here is an example of an attributive adjective, with monomorphemis adjective,
# which does not have morphological rule
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {adjectives}
Kayatenko      ti      balay a   dakkel
Kayat-en=ko    ti      balay a   dakkel
want-GF=1SG.ERG CORE.SG house LIG big
`I want the big house`

# Here is an example of an attributive adjective, fossilized.
# which does not have morphological rule
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {adjectives}
Kayatenko      ti      balay a   akaba
Kayat-en=ko    ti      balay a   akaba
want-GF=1SG.ERG CORE.SG house LIG wide
`I want the wide house`

# Here is a ungrammatical, contrasting example for attributive adjectives,
# where there is no LIG between Noun and ADJ
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: f
Phenomena: {adjectives}
Kayatenko      ti      nalabaga  balay
Kayat-en=ko    ti      na-labaga balay
want-GF=1SG.ERG CORE.SG ADJ-red   house
`I want the red house`

# ungrammatical adjectives as modifiers to nouns without LIG
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: f
Phenomena: {adjectives}
Kayatenko       ti      balay nalabaga
Kayat-en=ko     ti      balay na-labaga
want-GF=1SG.ERG CORE.SG house ADJ-red
`I want the red house`


######################################
######### ADVERBS ####################
######################################

# Because Ilocano adverbs could constitute a broad and diverse, only manner adverbs (such as English
# "quickly"-equivalenti) are considered.
# In Ilocano, such adverbial behavior can be achieved by use of an adjective, followed by Ilocano ligature, "(ng)a"
# (nga or a), which is followed by a verbal predicate.
# The word order is: adjective -> ligature -> finite clause
# Another way to achieve the adverbial behavior is by use of oblique noun marker, 'iti', followed by the adjective.
# Contrasting to the first method, where the word sequence of adjective and ligature happen before the finite clause,
# in this second method, a finite clause comes before the oblique noun marker and the adjective.
# The word order is: finite clause -> oblique noun marker -> adjective
# The oblique noun marker always needs to be the singular form of the oblique determiner, therefore,
# the plural form "dagiti" (CORE.PL) is not allowed.

# 1. use of an adjective with the ligature, "a":
Source: a:354
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {adverbs}
Nadaras  a   nagsubliak
na-daras a   n-ag-subli=ak
ADJ-fast ADV PF-AF-return=1SG.ABS
`I returned quickly`

# 2. Ungrammatical use of an adjective without ligature:
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: u
Phenomena: {adverbs}
Nadaras  nagsubliak
na-daras n-ag-subli=ak
ADJ-fast PF-AF-return=1SG.ABS
'I returned quickly'

# 2. use of an adjective or verb. connected to the predicate 
# as a prepositional phase with the oblique noun marker iti,
# similar to a prepositional phrase:
Source: a:354
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {adverbs}
Nagsangitak       iti napaut
n-ag-sangit=ak    iti na-paut
PF-AF-cry=1SG.ABS ADV ADJ-lasting
`I cried for a long time'

# adverbial with oblique followed by adjective should not use
# plural version of oblique
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: u
Phenomena: {adverbs}
Nagsangitak       dagiti napaut
n-ag-sangit=ak    dagiti na-paut
PF-AF-cry=1SG.ABS OBL.PL ADJ-lasting
`I cried for a long time'

# adverbial with oblique followed by adjective should not use
# core case determiner
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: u
Phenomena: {adverbs}
Nagsangitak      ti      napaut
n-ag-sangit=ak   ti      na-paut
PF-AF-cry=1SG.ABS CORE.SG ADJ-lasting
`I cried for a long time'

# ungrammatical: oblique noun marker is missing before the adjective
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: u
Phenomena: {adverbs}
Nagsangitak      napaut
n-ag-sangit=ak   na-paut
PF-AF-cry=1SG.ABS ADJ-lasting
`I cried for a long time'

Source: a:35
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {adverbs}
Nagpanunotka       iti nauneg
n-ag-panunot=ka    iti na-uneg
PF-AF-think=2SG.ABS ADV ADJ-deep
`You thought deeply`

# Ungrammatical example with ligature missing
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: u
Phenomena: {adverbs}
Nagpanunotka       nauneg  
n-ag-panunot=ka    na-uneg
PF-AF-think=2SG.ABS ADJ-deep
`You thought deeply`

Source: a:36
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {adverbs}
Nagsaoda            iti nalapat
n-ag-sao=da         iti na-lapat
PF-AF-speak=3PL.ABS ADV ADJ-frank
`They spoke frankly`


