######################################
######### POSSESSIVE #################
######################################

# Ilocano pronominal possesives, such as 'my', 'their, 'your', etc,
# are achieved by the use of a noun with an enclitic pronoun in ergative
# case.
# From page 117:
# Normally, a possessor follows the possessed referent. possessive constructions are done
# simply by juxtaposing possessum and possessor. A possessor may be encoded with a full noun
# phrase (the appropriate article introducing the relevant nominal possessor) or an ergative enclitic
# pronoun.

# grammatically correct possessive, using ergative enclitic pronoun
Source: a:117
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {possessives}
Nakita   ti      babai ti      balayko
na-kita  ti      babai ti      balay=ko
PF.GF-see CORE.SG girl  CORE.SG house=1SG.ERG
`The girl saw my house'

# from p.384:
# possession in Ilocano can be expressed by simple juxtaposition of
# the possessed entity and possessor. in that order.
Source: a:117
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {possessives}
Nakitako         ti      tulbek ti      lalaki
na-kita=ko       ti      tulbek ti      lalaki
PF.GF-see=1SG.ERG CORE.SG key    CORE.SG boy
`I saw the boy's key'

# Though cannot find exact source, goal focus verb with core NP as subject,
# followed by the possesum NP and possessor NP seems theoretically possible
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {possessives}
Nakita   ti      babai ti      tulbek ti      lalaki
na-kita  ti      babai ti      tulbek ti      lalaki
PF.GF-see CORE.SG girl  CORE.SG key    CORE.SG boy
`The girl saw the boy's key'

# incorrect case for possessive, using absolutive enclitic pronoun
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: u
Phenomena: {case}
Nakita   ti      babai ti      balayak
na-kita  ti      babai ti      balay=ak
PF.GF-see CORE.SG girl  CORE.SG house=1SG.ABS
`The girl saw my house'

# possessive nominal needs CORE.SG determiner before the 3rdPerson noun
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: u
Phenomena: {case}
Nakita   ti      babai balayak
na-kita  ti      babai balay=ak
PF.GF-see CORE.SG girl  house=1SG.ABS
`The girl saw my house'

# Example from page a:117 but substituted a person's name (ni Maria) with a noun (ti babai)
# This is the case where two NPs are juxtaposed
Source: a:117
Vetted: f
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {possessives}
nakitako         ti      balay ti      babai
na-kita=ko       ti      balay ti      babai
PF.GF-see=1SG.ERG CORE.SG house CORE.SG girl
'I saw the girl's house'

# This is the case where tww NPs are juxtaposed but for actor focus, the object is
# in the oblique case, followed by the possessor, which needs to be in core case
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {possessives}
nagkitaak        iti    balay ti      babai
n-ag-kita=ak     iti    balay ti      babai
PF-AF-see=1SG.ABS OBL.SG house CORE.SG girl
'I saw the girl's house'

# two oblique case juxtaposed is not describing possessives
Source: author
Vetted: f
Judgment: u
Phenomena: {possessives}
nagkitaak        iti     balay iti    babai
n-ag-kita=ak     iti     balay iti    babai
PF-AF-see=1SG.ABS CORE.SG house OBL.SG girl
'I saw the girl's house'

# Week 5
